C# Getting Started 
Welcome to the world of C# application development! In this assignment, you will 
create a C# application from scratch, focusing on the fundamental concepts and 
features of the language. Follow the instructions below to complete the assignment 
and get started with C#. 
Task 1: Environment Setup 
1. Install Visual Studio: 
• Download and install the latest version of Visual Studio from the official 
Microsoft website. 
• Ensure that you select the appropriate version for your operating 
system. 
2. Create a New Project: 
• Launch Visual Studio and select "Create a new project" from the startup 
window. 
• Choose a suitable project template, such as "Console App (.NET Core)," 
and provide a name for your project. 
• Select a location to save your project files and click "Create" or "OK" to 
create the project. 
Task 2: Writing Basic Code 
8 
1. Familiarize yourself with the Project Structure: 
• Observe the default files and folders generated for a console 
application, such as Program.cs, Properties, and the project file (.csproj). 
• Understand the purpose of each file and folder in the project structure. 
2. Open the Program.cs file in the code editor. 
• Notice the generated code that contains the entry point of the program 
in the Main() method. 
3. Write some simple C# code: 
• Experiment with different code snippets, such as displaying messages 
on the console using Console.WriteLine(). 
• Practice using variables, data types, and basic arithmetic operations. 
4. Build and Run your application: 
• Use the "Build" menu or the keyboard shortcut Ctrl+Shift+B to build 
your project. 
• Press F5 or use the "Debug" menu to run your application. 
• Observe the output in the console window and ensure that your code 
executes correctly. 
• Also think about Why we need to build and what this Build operation will 
accomplish? 
Task 3: Exploring Language Features 
1. Variables and Data Types: 
• Declare and initialize variables of different data types, such as int, 
double, string, and bool. 
• Perform operations and manipulate data using appropriate operators 
and methods. 
2. Control Flow Statements: 
• Use if-else statements and switch statements to implement conditional 
logic. 
• Utilize loops, such as for loops and while loops, to iterate over 
collections or perform repetitive tasks. 
3. Functions and Methods: 
• Create custom functions with different return types and parameters. 
• Implement proper function and method encapsulation and naming 
conventions. 
4. Arrays and Collections: 
9 
• Declare and manipulate arrays to store and access multiple values of the 
same type. 
• Explore built-in collection classes like List<T> and Dictionary<TKey, 
TValue>. 
Task 4: Explore on Handling User Input 
1. Prompting User Input: 
• Use the Console.WriteLine() method to display a message and prompt 
the user for input. 
• Use the Console.ReadLine() method to read and store user input. 
2. Parsing and Validating User Input: 
• Convert user input to the appropriate data type using parsing methods 
like int.TryParse() or double.TryParse(). 
• Implement basic validation to ensure that user input meets certain 
criteria (e.g., numeric input, within a specific range). 
Task 5: Building a Functional Application 
1. Understand the application requirements: Basic Contact Manager Console 
Application 
• Create a simple console-based contact manager application that allows 
users to store and manage their contacts. The application should have 
the following requirements: 
• Contact Information: 
1. The application should allow users to enter contact information, 
including name, phone number, email address, and any 
additional notes. 
• Contact List: 
1. The application should maintain an in-memory list of contacts, 
allowing users to view, add, edit, and delete contacts. 
2. The contact list should display the name of each contact for easy 
identification. 
• Search Functionality: 
1. Users should be able to search for contacts based on their names 
or other relevant details. 
2. The search functionality should display the matching contacts or 
indicate if no results are found. 
• User Interface: 
10 
1. The application should provide a console-based user interface to 
interact with the contact manager. 
2. Use appropriate console input and output methods to display 
and manipulate contact information. 
3. Consider using a menu system to allow users to access different 
functionalities. 
• Error Handling: 
1. Implement proper error-handling mechanisms to prevent crashes 
and handle exceptions gracefully. Try to learn the basis of try
catch statements in C#. Later during the TIPS journey, you will 
learn error handling in detail. 
2. Display meaningful error messages to users in case of input 
validation failures or unexpected errors. 
• Data Persistence: 
1. As the application is based on in-memory storage, the contact 
data will be lost when the application is closed or restarted. 
2. Data persistence beyond the application's runtime is not required 
for this version. 
• User Experience: 
1. Ensure that the application provides a smooth and intuitive user 
experience within the console environment. 
2. Implement features like sorting contacts, displaying contact 
details, or providing keyboard shortcuts for common actions. 
• Documentation: 
1. Include clear instructions for running the application and 
interacting with its features within the console. 
2. Provide any additional notes or considerations regarding the 
application's functionality and usage. 
• Note: This version of the application utilizes in-memory storage for 
simplicity and getting started purposes. It does not persist contact data 
beyond the application's runtime. Feel free to enhance the functionality 
or consider implementing data persistence using a file or database if 
desired. 
2. Define the Application Structure: 
• Determine the necessary functionalities and user interactions. 
• Plan and design the classes, methods, and variables required for your 
application. 
3. Implement the Application: 
• Write the necessary code to create the desired application. 
• Test and debug your code to ensure proper functionality. 
4. Enhance the Application: 
• Implement proper exception handling to handle errors gracefully. 
11 
• Optimize the application for performance and efficiency. 
• Apply proper coding conventions and naming conventions. 
Development Requirements: 
1. Proper Documentation: 
• Provide clear and concise comments throughout your code to explain 
the purpose and functionality of each section. 
• Write a README file that includes instructions for running the 
application and any additional notes or considerations. 
2. Code Organization: 
• Use meaningful and descriptive names for variables, functions, and 
classes. 
• Organize your code into logical sections and separate concerns to 
improve readability and maintainability. 
3. Error Handling: 
• Implement appropriate error-handling techniques, such as try-catch 
blocks, to handle exceptions and prevent application crashes. 
4. User-Friendly Interface (Even Be it Console        
): 
• Design a user interface that provides clear instructions and meaningful 
feedback to users. 
• Consider usability and accessibility when designing the user interface. 
